oned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a figure for the percentage a year or two ago of children’s homes inspectors who came from the social care sector. (Q.52). If she had that figure to hand and could supply it to us that would be great.</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-3.3pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> inspectors who are deployed to inspect children’s homes have a social care background. In the past four years </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has recruited 54 new Social Care Regulatory Inspectors from the social care sector, 47 of whom are still employed. For context, the total number of Social Care Regulatory Inspectors is 135 (FTE).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; text-transform:uppercase"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">Am I right in thinking that, according to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">, the Statutory Guidance on Children Who Run Away and Go Missing from Home or Care (the Statutory Guidance) technically only applies to local authorities? If so, does this create real, practical problems for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none"> (and/or others) in terms of regulation and enforcement or is it just a technical, theoretical problem. (Q.70)</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">Lisa Pascoe was not referring that guidance – she was referring to </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/ABOUTDFE/STATUTORY/G00222870/CHILDREN-ACT-1989-CHILDRENS-HOMES"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline; text-transform:none">this</span></a><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">. </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">Ofsted</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none"> is unable to regulate effectively against this guidance for any providers although we can make recommendations against this as a good practice guide.</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none"> As this guidance is released under the Local Authority and Social Services Act 1970 it is primarily aimed at local authorities. Given that it is released to local authorities we think it would have more impact if it spoke explicitly to local authorities as commissioners of services. </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">We also think that there is lots of valuable information on here for all providers and </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">it would be more helpful to the sector if this guidance was all contained in one place alongside the kind of guidance we would like to see in the new national quality standards. The current national minimum standards reference the statutory guidance on children who run away. We are only able to enforce against a breach of regulations. Where providers do not meet the NMS or follow statutory guidance we need to demonstrate that this is then a failure to meet a regulation. We will be much better placed to take enforcement action if there are new regulations that have more aspiration for children and young people and are more closely linked with the underpinning standards that are not based on a minimum standard.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Was Lisa’s recommendation as follows: to put some of the information for providers of children’s homes that is currently in the Statutory Guidance into the National Minimum Standards (NMS) instead? The phrase National Quality Standards and was mentioned and I was not sure how this differed from the NMS so if you could clarify this in your answer that would be great.(Q.70 and 71)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> would like to be in a strengthened position whereby all providers (whether local authority or independent) who are not providing good care or experiences for children and young people can be quickly and clearly made to improve with the full force of enforcement action and possible closure available. The proposal for regulations should effect this change. </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> would like to see a move away from the concept of ‘minimum’ and therefore move from something called NMS to something that is called ‘national quality standards’ or similar and has higher aspirations for children and young people. On this basis the standards would need re-writing. </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> would like to see some of the helpful guidance that is within the statutory guidance currently (as referenced above)</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">moved into one place for all providers. This place would logically be the new national quality standards.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Was the second part of Lisa’s recommendation to redraft the Statutory Guidance (mentioned above) so that it contains information directly relating to the role of local authorities as commissioners? (Q.71)</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Yes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As you may know, there have been some suggestions that many local authorities have not been complying with their duties to notify area authorities when they place looked after children in out of authority placements. Hence, the Government’s proposals to ensure that children’s homes also notify the area authority when children are admitted to, or discharged from, their home. We have heard a suggestion that monitoring compliance by local authorities with their notification duties should be part of the inspection framework that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> uses and that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> should enforce the requirement on placing authorities to notify. Could I just check, under the new Single Inspection Framework, is this now built in and does </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> have any views about how satisfactory this is likely to be and whether it will need further powers to enforce compliance with this duty? Is it also happy that it would have sufficient powers under the Government’s proposals to enforce the notification duty that children’s homes will have?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofsted</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> will be tracking individual children and young people’s experiences and having a much stronger focus on those children and young people placed out of authority including visiting children and young people living in children’s homes outside their local authority area. This is so we can see how well these young people are supported. We have no enforcement powers with local authorities but wherever we identify weaknesses we will make this clear in the report and clearly identify our expectations for improvement. Our management information evidence that is required for this inspection asks LAs to show that an out of area placement is being authorised by a senior manager and that includes the notification to that area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In individual children’s homes we will be able to test how well the home has undertaken this new duty and if it is a requirement in regulation we can take appropriate action where needed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>